And the wall collapsed …
Here's a quiz for history buffs: 20 years ago, the year 1989 was a fateful year marked by three events that all took place on June 4th.
Which one do you remember best and which had the most significant consequences for the planet?
a) The bloody crackdown at Tiananmen Square
b) The death of Ayatollah Khomeini in Iran
c) The elections in Poland
Few are those who answer c).
For the events in Beijing and the death of Khomeini, which made the headlines, have overshadowed the victory of the famous opposition union Solidarnosc during the first free election in Eastern Europe since 1946.
Yet, nothing contributed more to the collapse of communism in Europe - and therefore to the re-foundation of the post-war international order.
There will be all sorts of commemorations of the end of communism in the coming months, including the anniversary of the fall of the Berlin Wall in November 1989.
For many people, it was an hour of glory, emblematic of the West's victory at the end of the Cold War, a victory whose origins are unknown.
But having witnessed the collapse of the Eastern bloc from the beginning, one realizes that the process was long and complex.
The election in Poland was a turning point, the moment when the movement in favor of change became irreversible.
It had gained strength after a summer of strikes, when the communist leader at the head of Poland, General Jaruzelski, considered that the country's economic problems were too serious for him to face alone.
Why not turn to the Polish opposition, he said - if not to find a solution - at least to share the responsibility for the situation with them?
After six months of bargaining, he reached a historic agreement: there would be free and fair legislative elections and Solidarnosc would be allowed to participate.
The communist leaders (no more than Solidarnosc) did not even consider for a moment that they could lose.
Even in their darkest nightmares, they did not imagine that they would be driven from power.
Yet, this is exactly what happened.
In retrospect, it is surprising that there could have been any doubts.
Solidarity made its audacious campaign.
A celebrated poster, repurposed for the occasion, that of a classic western film, High Noon, experienced great success: it shows a Gary Cooper holding a ballot paper instead of a revolver, playing the role of the sheriff.
June 4th was the day of judgment.
On this bright Sunday morning, as spring was giving birth to summer, voters sent the Polish communists to the slaughterhouse.
For their last day in power, the Polish communists resorted to a final perversity that turned into an unintentional self-humiliation.
They designed an electoral system in which Poles, instead of selecting their preferred candidates, had to cross out the names of those they did not want - in other words, all the communists listed on the ballots.
Everywhere one looked, people were getting rid of the hated autocrats.
This was finally the popular uprising that Poland had long been waiting for, the revenge on December 1980, when Jaruzelski declared martial law, banned Solidarity and threw its leaders into prison.
The revolution by the pen!
Handled with style, the pen that ultimately triumphs over the sword becomes the weapon of a glorious revenge.
Certain voters tore their ballots completely, thus decapitating the old regime with an effective coup de main.
Others savored the moment, perhaps they were smoking a cigarette while crossing out names on the ballots.
"That one put my cousin in prison," Pfft!, "Hey, this apparatchik got rich off our scarcity," Pfft !
Pfft !
On the other hand, the communist campaign went almost unnoticed.
Throughout Warsaw, only two government candidates bothered to put up posters.
Most relied on the monopoly they had in the media to get their message across: "Vote for Lezek, a good communist".
It can be said to his credit that the regime acknowledged its defeat with remarkable grace.
The day after the elections, at three in the afternoon, Jaruzelski gathered the main party officials to tell them: "Our defeat is total," we need to find a political solution."
He thus indicated that he wanted neither violence nor rigging, the communists would have to live with the election result.
Twenty years later, I am still perplexed.
Those of us who covered Eastern Europe knew that Solidarnosc was going to win.
We also knew that this peaceful victory would be an example for the rest of the Eastern bloc.
The vote in Poland was extremely encouraging for anti-communists around the world.
Thanks to Poland, what seemed impossible just a few days earlier suddenly became achievable.
There were other signs.
In May, Hungarian reformers began tearing down the fences erected on the border with Austria - a hole in the Iron Curtain.
In Moscow, Mikhail Gorbachev spoke of a "Common European Home" and rejected Brezhnev's interventionist doctrine.
Yet when the wall fell, political leaders and experts unanimously acknowledged: "We saw nothing coming".
The Cold War lasted so long that any change seemed impossible - until the day freedom erupted.
